# UniPilot AI Processing

Long-running AI requests MUST be processed asynchronously. The API must never block on a slow model call.

## Async / Background Processing (mandatory)
- Long AI requests must run in a background worker, not inline in the request handler.
- The API enqueues a job (via Redis queue) and returns immediately with a job/task id and `202 Accepted` (or similar).
- The client polls a status endpoint or receives the result once processing completes.
- The worker is a separate internal container that consumes the queue.

## Job Lifecycle
- Track each job's state: `pending` -> `processing` -> `completed` / `failed`.
- Persist job state and results in MongoDB so they survive restarts.
- Store enough metadata to return status and final result to the owning student.

## Internal AI Service
- The AI service stays on the internal network; it is never exposed to clients.
- Calls go API/worker -> internal AI service. Clients never reach the AI service directly.
- Load any external AI provider keys from environment variables.

## Resilience & Limits
- Apply rate limiting to all AI-triggering endpoints (shared Redis store).
- Set timeouts and a bounded retry policy for AI/provider calls; mark a job `failed` after retries are exhausted.
- Handle provider errors gracefully and store a user-friendly failure message — never leak provider internals or keys.
- Validate AI responses before persisting or returning them (treat them as untrusted input).

## Authorization
- AI endpoints and job-status endpoints are protected: a student may only access their own jobs/results (check the JWT user id).

## Testing
- Mock the AI provider in unit/integration tests.
- Cover enqueue -> process -> result retrieval in E2E tests.
- Include a stress test for the AI endpoint and the queue.
